in Industrial IoT (IIoT). The data stream in IIoT is characterized by large volume, strong real-time, and diversified information transmission [1], [2], [3], which is difficult to identify and classify. This will affect subsequent applications such as fault detection, and further pose a threat to the security of wireless communication. With the development of specific emitter identification (SEI), SEI can use the unique radio frequency (RF) fingerprint of the emitter to measure the characteristics of the received RF and determine the emitter generating the signal according to the existing prior information, thus realizing the classification and identification of the data stream. It can be seen that SEI [4], [5] is of great significance in the field of IIoT. In recent years, artificial intelligence (AI) methods, including machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL), have made great achievements in the field of signal processing, such as automatic modulation recognition [6], [7], [8], [9], channel state information prediction and feedback [10], [11], malware traffic classification [12], [13], [14], flight delay prediction [15], and other applications. Nevertheless, these SEI methods based on ML or DL all require accurate data to operate, and their convergence is not good for data with large sample distribution deviation, multiple categories, and multiple targets. In addition, the transferability of the results of DL has certain limitations, and the results of training are difficult to apply to other problems. For the ML method, it is difficult to get the best performance through the adaptive method. Meanwhile, to extract sufficient but minimal information from the data, manual selection of effective features is chosen to reduce the number of features in the linear model [16], [17], [18]. However, this method is inefficient in dealing with large amounts of data and performs poorly in terms of identification accuracy. More importantly, this method relies heavily on abundant prior knowledge from experts. For this reason, we consider combining the adaptive feature combination (AFC) algorithm with DL. The existing SEI methods only pay attention to the single data set, without in-depth feature mining and also without considering the best combination of features. In addition, for RF signals, there is no library related to their features currently. However, building such a knowledge library of RF signal features can help provide valuable information reference for RF signal identification, and it can make the signal features more portable. The knowledge graph (KG)
