technology has the above advantages. KG is essentially the knowledge library of semantic network, and has the ability to formalize complex and scattered knowledge, and can realize fast semantic search [19]. Through the four steps of data mining, information processing, knowledge measurement, and graphic rendering, this technology can effectively represent the relationships between different entities and can analyze semantics to the greatest extent [20]. Furthermore, it realizes the visualization of information, which greatly reduces the obstacles for users to quickly create effective data visualization [21]. Last but not least, it gives semantic meaning to data and further improves the efficiency and interpretability of information. Therefore, this article considers introducing the KG into the SEI technique and proving its feasibility [22]. Therefore, in the complex environment of the IIoT, for multisource signals with large amount of data and strong real time, this article aims to propose an SEI based on adaptive signal feature embedded KG. The main contributions of this article are highlighted as follows. 1) To solve the problem of manual selection of effective features from several signal features, this article uses AFC block to achieve the best feature combination strategy. The AFC block analogizes signal features as different channels and then obtains the best weight of each feature. 2) In this article, different compression rates are considered in the process of the AFC block, which can achieve the best balance between the identification performance and the computation overhead. 3) To deal with the visual representation and storage of signal features, this article innovatively constructs a KG for signal features with the help of Neo4j [23]. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first attempt to apply KG to SEI technology. Note: The main symbols in this article are listed in Table I.
II. RELATED WORKS
In this section, we provide an overview of existing SEI methods, as shown in Table II, including traditional methods based on ML, and automatic methods based on DL. More so, we make a review of several KG classification methods for different tasks.
A. ML-Based SEI Methods
ML-based methods were first proposed for SEI. For the most universal discrete data, the supervised ML method has become the first choice of many scholars. Zhou et al. [24] proposed a new cluster-based k-nearest neighbor (kNN) method. This method uses the new kNN algorithm to classify and dynamically adjust the number of neighborhood k in each iteration, which solves the problem of low classification accuracy when the training samples are uneven. Guo et al. [25] used support vector machine (SVM) and random forest (RF) to identify relevant features with great impact from multisource remote sensing data. The authors confirm that the optimal SVM model based on feature selection improves the identification accuracy through feature selection. The structured SVM proposed by Zhang and Piccardi [26] is an extension of SVM, which
TABLE I MAIN SYMBOLS IN THIS ARTICLE
is used to jointly predict structured labels from multiple measurements, effectively realizing the classification of two challenging data sets. Unfortunately, existing SVM methods are often used in binary classification situations, so it is difficult to apply them to handle multiclassification problems. Gupta et al. [27] innovatively proposed the use of OneVsRest classifier on the basis of SVM, which achieves great success in multiclassification problems. Moreover, Wang et al. [28] proposed a novel FS-SEI method based on deep metric ensemble learning (DMEL). Metric learning with a complexvalued convolutional neural network (CNN) is used for feature embedding to extract distinguishable features with compact intraclass distance and separable interclass distance. However, the above ML-based SEI methods are very sensitive to the missing data and often result in a slight lack of accuracy.
B. DL-Based SEI Methods
In the past decade, with the great success of DL in the field of image processing, scholars have gradually applied it to signal processing, especially SEI. Hu et al. [29] proposed the squeeze-and-excitation network, which can adaptively recalibrate the channel feature correspondence by modeling the interdependencies between channels to significantly improve CNN performance. Merchant et al. [30] took the lead in designing a CNN to detect physical features for the identification of cognitive radio devices, and the method showed great transferability and robustness. Baldini and Giuliani [31] further considered CNN for SEI tasks and proposed a DL method based on stacked neural networks for classification.
