HUA et al.: SPECIFIC EMITTER IDENTIFICATION USING ADAPTIVE SIGNAL FEATURE EMBEDDED KNOWLEDGE GRAPH 4725
feature extractors. After that, the features are taken as the input of the KG-AFC architecture, thus it can generate a visual KG. Moreover, the attention mechanism is used to process the feature nodes, so that the computational resources are biased toward valuable and meaningful features. Finally, according to the feature identification results, unauthorized illegal devices are found.
B. Problem Formulation
Based on the system model above and the signal data set, the received RF signal in this article can be expressed as
xi(t) = si(t) + ni(t), i = 1, 2, . . . , N (1)
where xi(t) represents the received RF signal, si(t) represents the RF signal input to the channel after modulation, and ni(t) represents the additive white Gaussian noise. It is well known that SEI technology is essential to solve the matching problem between the received RF signal and the corresponding label [38], [39], [40]. This article assumes that the data set is defined as {xi, yi}N
i=1, where yi represents the label corresponding to different emitters, then the SEI problem to be solved can be defined as
