IV. PROPOSED SEI METHOD USING KG-AFC ARCHITECTURE
Presently, most SEI methods are based on the ML algorithm. However, the classification accuracy of the mainstream ML-based SVM algorithm for large-scale training samples is far from that of the SEI method based on the DL-based algorithm, which has approximately 1%–7% performance increase in SEI task [41]. Meanwhile, the ML method needs to manually select effective features when facing a large number of features, and the training method is complex and cumbersome. Therefore, this article proposes the DL-based KG-AFC architecture, which can be used for SEI. In this section, the proposed SEI method using KG-AFC architecture is introduced in detail, including the feature extraction, the generation of KG, visualization, and the AFC block in KG-AFC architecture.
A. Feature Extraction
For RF signals, there are two main types of features that are most commonly used and effective, namely, time-domain features and frequency-domain features [42], [43]. In addition, due to the significant influence of frequency features on RF signals, spectral kurtosis can detect and characterize the nonstationary nature of the signal, effectively identifying transient shocks and their distribution in the frequency band from signals containing background noise, and is an effective supplement to frequency features [44]. Therefore, in the feature extraction section of this article, the most commonly used time-domain features, frequency-domain features, and spectral kurtosis features are selected. In this article, the mean, variance, standard deviation, kurtosis, skewness, fourth-order cumulant, sixth-order cumulant, maximum, minimum, median, peak-to-peak, rectified mean value, mean-square value, root mean-square, root mean-square amplitude, waveform factor, peak factor, pulse factor, clearance factor, etc., are selected as the signal features extracted in the time domain. Moreover, gravity frequency, mean-square frequency, root mean-square frequency, frequency variance, frequency standard deviation, etc., are selected as the signal features extracted in the frequency domain. Last but not least, the mean value of spectral kurtosis, standard deviation of spectral kurtosis, kurtosis of spectral kurtosis, skewness of spectral kurtosis, etc., are selected as extracted spectral kurtosis features to construct the RF signal KG. 1) Higher Order Cumulant: We extract the characteristics of commonly used fourth-order cumulants and sixth-order cumulants. The extraction principle is shown below. A received signal with noise is shown in (1), where s(t) is represented by
