B. KG-AFC Architecture
After extracting the signal features of the real part and the imaginary part of the collected original RF signal, respectively, 56 RF signal features are obtained. This article further proposes the KG-AFC architecture that can be used for SEI tasks. This section introduces the generation and visualization process of KG and the adaptive feature selection by AFC block. 1) Generation of KG: The RF signal KG is based on the RF signal feature library. To realize data sharing and data centralized control, before generating the KG, the signal features x′ are imported into the MySQL database to generate the RF signal feature library. Based on the RF signal feature library, the RF KG is generated by artificially establishing the relationship between entities and attributes using prior expert knowledge, the specific method is: we choose the form of “RF signal − time-domain features − feature parameter” and “RF signal − frequency-domain features − feature parameter” to form the corresponding “entity − attribute” format, taking the timedomain features and frequency-domain features as entities, and taking their corresponding feature parameters as subsidiary attributes to connect the relationship between entities through attributes. For example, the “time-domain features” entity and the “mean” attribute connect the entities and attributes through the “mean: real part” relationship, forming a simple triple format. This construction method is not only conducive to the systematic characterization of data but also facilitates the subsequent SEI and analysis. 2) Visualization: Due to the visualization assistance of KG enhances the model’s representation ability and further expands the application boundaries of KG, we use Neo4j
Authorized licensed use limited to: GUANGZHOU UNIVERSITY. Downloaded on September 25,2024 at 02:59:11 UTC from IEEE Xplore. Restrictions apply.


HUA et al.: SPECIFIC EMITTER IDENTIFICATION USING ADAPTIVE SIGNAL FEATURE EMBEDDED KNOWLEDGE GRAPH 4727
to visualize the relationships between various entities and attributes. At the same time, MySQL Workbench is used to realize the visualization of various discrete feature value, which is convenient for subsequent addition, deletion, and modification of data. 3) AFC Block: The AFC block adaptively recalibrates channel-wise feature responses by explicitly modeling interdependencies between channels. We use this method of adding an attention mechanism in the channel dimension, i.e., AFC block, to obtain the importance of the feature channel (the channel dimension in this article is the extracted feature). After that, use this importance to assign different weights to each feature channel. Thus, the weight of features useful for the current SEI task is increased, and the weight of features not useful for it is suppressed, so as to achieve the purpose of adaptive signal features. In this article, the specific use of AFC block is shown in Fig. 2. First, perform the squeeze and compress the 2-D features (H × W) of each channel into a real number through average pooling. After the squeeze, the dimension becomes 1×1×C, where C represents the number of features in the feature extraction module. That is to say, z ∈ RC is the result of the global average pooling of features in the spatial dimension H × W, which can be expressed as
z = Fsq
(x′) = 1
H×W
H ∑
m=1
W ∑
n=1
x′(m, n). (20)
Second, to fully capture the dependencies between features, we have to require the architecture to be able to learn the nonlinear relationships between channel features and to enhance the multiple channel features that we hope to be effective. Based on this, we choose to use a simple gating mechanism with sigmoid activation. We map and transform feature vectors through two FCs. Among them, the number of neurons in the first FC needs to be divided by a reduction ratio, which represents the compression ratio. Thus, the following transformation form is adopted:
s = Fex(z, W) = σ (g(z, W)) = σ (W2δ(W1z)) (21)
where z is the output of squeeze; W1 is an FC operation with
W1 ∈ RC/r×C; δ represents the Relu operation; W2 is also an
FC operation with W2 ∈ RC×C/r; g(z, W) represents two FC operations; and σ represents the sigmoid operation. Through the two FC nonlinear operations, the correlation between features can be used to train the true scale. In addition, the first FC compresses C channels into C/r channels, which can reduce the amount of computation. By this method, we can achieve the balance between the overall performance and the amount of computation. Finally, the weight vector obtained is multiplied with the channel to complete the introduction of the attention mechanism in the channel dimension is given as
 ̃x = Fscale
(x′, s) = s × x′. (22)
Algorithm 1: Algorithm Statement of the Proposed SEI Method Using KG-AFC
Input : RF signal after KG for training Xtrain; Corresponding real labels for training Ytrain; Compression ratio in AFC block r; Output : Final weighted features  ̃x;
1 [Model construction and parameter setting]:
2 Load Xtrain, Ytrain;
3 Construct KG-AFC model by Fig. 2, and choose cross entropy loss LCE as loss function;
4 Initialize the feature weight s0; 5 Set parameters, including the number of training epochs N = 200, the batch size Sbatch = 32, initial learning rate η; 6 [Data mapping phase]:
7 Reduce the dimension of channel features by (20), i.e., z 8 Perform a compression transformation through an FC, i.e., W1 and reduce the data in z to r times the original in (21); 9 Perform feature mapping transformation through the other FC, i.e., W2 and decompress the data in (21);
10 Record two FC operations in (21) as g(z, W); 11 Perform sigmoid operation to get the final feature weight matrix s in (21); 12 [Training phase]: 13 s = s0, n∗ = 0;
14 Initialize the operation parameter W∗; 15 for n = 1, 2, . . . , N do
16 Update s by Adam, η and g(z, W);
17 if LCE[g(z, Wn)] < LCE[g(z, W∗)] then
18 W∗ = Wn;
19 n∗ = n;
20 s = sn; 21 end 22 end 23 return s
24 Multiply the obtained weight matrix s with the channel feature to obtain the final feature x ̃ through (22).
C. Summary and Workflow
In summary, the SEI method using KG-AFC based on adaptive signal feature embedded KG can intuitively represent extracted features through KG. In addition, the AFC strategy can be realized through the feature weight layer based on the attention mechanism. Most importantly, it can achieve a balance between performance and computation overhead. The workflow of the proposed KG-AFC is shown in Algorithm 1. For the convenience of understanding the algorithm, we use a sample as an example and explain the operation process in conjunction with Algorithm 1. First, input the sample into the feature extraction module, which includes common multidomain features of RF signals, and normalize them to obtain the output x′. Next, utilizing expert prior knowledge, input the obtained output x′ into KG and obtain the corresponding visualization graph in Neo4j. Afterward, AFC is performed on the output data through the channel attention mechanism. First, compress the global spatial information using (20) to obtain the output z. Second, the dimension reduction and effective features are selected by two FCs, and different weight matrices s corresponding to different features are obtained. Finally, the weight matrix s is multiplied by the original features to obtain the adaptive optimal feature  ̃x.
