Fig. 2. Illustration of the flowchart of AFC block. The AFC block first squeezes to reduce the dimension of channel features; second, performs compression transformation to reduce complexity; and finally, performs feature mapping transformation to fully capture the relationships between features and achieve AFC.
V. EXPERIMENTAL RESULTS
We will introduce data set generation and parameter settings, feature library and KG construction results, and simulation results for the SEI task. We then give some analysis and discussion about the results, including performance, complexity, and influence of different compression ratios in the AFC block.
A. Data Set Generation and Parameter Settings
The data set used in this article is a continuous signal sample generated by the collection device. As shown in Fig. 3, the collection device consists of a signal generator (VSG60A), a signal receiver (BB60C), two personal computers (PCs), and a target power amplifier (PA) [46], [47]. One of the PCs is connected to VSG60A via USB 3.0 to observe the original signal waveform generated by VSG60A. Then, the signal is sent to PA, which can effectively utilize the amplification effect of the internal transistor to achieve continuous current amplification and complete power amplification. Further enhanced the function of the collected signal. Next, the signal passes through a real communication environment and is collected by BB60C. Finally, add noise to the received signal and normalize it. At this point, the entire signal collection process has been completed. We consider using VSG60A and BB60C as signal generators and receivers in this article, respectively. Its brief introduction and implementation functions are as follows: the VSG60A RF vector signal source can generate a variety of RF signal with different modulation modes to satisfy different functions. The frequency range is as high as 6 GHz, which can easily meet the requirements of different modulation modes of signal. In this article, we choose the commonly used modulation method of 16PSK, which can generate multiple modulation types of signal based on VSG60A. In future work, we will consider using it to generate more diverse RF signal and explore SEI problems in multitask scenarios. BB60C is a 6-GHz real-time spectrum analyzer module and RF recorder, capable of 250 kHz–27 MHz variable acquisition of IQ data and amplitude correction. We use BB60C to convert the
Fig. 3. Illustration of signal collection system.
TABLE III SIGNAL PARAMETERS LIST AND DEFAULT VALUES
received signal into a digital signal and transmit it to a PC for normalization processing and slicing. To create a unified generalized feature database, we referred to the data paradigm proposed by Tu et al. [48], and set the number of individual samples to 12 000. Considering that the longer the reading length of a single sample, the smaller the ratio of the absolute value of error to the measured value, and the higher the identification accuracy, we set the reading length of a single sample as 12 000. In addition, in practical applications, due to the complexity of the signal and its higher harmonic frequency, the sampling frequency should be set higher and the sampling points should be more dense, making the obtained discrete signal closer to the original signal. Therefore, this article adopts a sampling frequency of 10 MHz. Thus, the IQ signal parsed by each PA is 6000 sample points. The parameter settings are shown in Table III. All the simulation experiments are completed in the CentOS 7.0 working environment, which can support Torch 1.12 and Python 3.9. The working environment is also equipped with four Nvidia RTX 2080Ti GPUs, which can get the simulation results more efficiently. In addition, MySQL database, MySQL
