Workbench, and Neo4j are also used for the construction and visual representation of KG. In the SEI task, the parameter settings are shown in Table IV.
B. Feature Library and Knowledge Graph
In this article, we use MATLAB to extract features of the original RF signal according to the real part and the imaginary part, and splice the extracted features to get the signal feature of the input KG-AFC architecture as X ∈ R36000×56. Then import it into MySQL database to generate feature library and use MySQL Workbench to realize visualization. The visualization interface of MySQL Workbench is shown in Fig. 4. Based on the constructed feature library, the RF signal KG is constructed by artificially establishing the relationship between entities and attributes using prior expert knowledge, and the KG is visualized using Neo4j. For the convenience of viewing, select one of the data at random for Neo4j visual representation, as shown in Fig. 5.
C. Comparison of Different Compression Ratios
The proposed KG-AFC algorithm architecture has a certain flexibility due to the nonlinear interaction between learning channel features. At the same time, in this article, we consider different compression ratios to choose the best compression ratio to achieve a balance between performance and complexity. For the SEI task, the compression ratios we consider for comparison are r = {2, 4, 8, 16, 32}.
1) Performance of Different Compression Ratios: We select the compression ratio above for Monte Carlo simulation, and run 100 times for each compression ratio. Through Monte Carlo simulation results, the performance under different compression ratios is analyzed and discussed. Here, the detailed results of 100 Monte Carlo simulations are shown by box plot, which can be found in Fig. 6. The box plot cannot be affected by outliers, can accurately and stably depict the discrete distribution of data, and is also conducive to data cleaning. It can display the maximum, minimum, median, upper, and lower quartiles of a group of data. Among them, the black line in the middle of the box is the median, representing the average level of the data; the upper and lower limits of the box are the upper and lower quartiles of the data, which can reflect the fluctuation of the data to a certain extent; and black “o” represents the outlier and two black horizontal lines visually mean the maximum and minimum values in the case of removing outliers. In addition, to better reflect the changing process of
identification accuracy under different compression ratios r, we take the medium value when r = 2 as the baseline. From the box plot of identification accuracy for the KGAFC algorithm, we can find that when r = {8, 16, 32}, there are many discrete points in the result, and the result shows a certain randomness and is not stable. However, in the case of r = {2, 4}, the number of discrete points is small and the identification accuracy is relatively stable. Through further comparison with the original identification accuracy without compression, we find that within the range of r = {2, 4, 8}, the fluctuation amplitude of the data in the box is relatively small, and the data is relatively concentrated. This means that the identification performance fluctuates less, and it can be considered that the performance is robust within this range. In addition, according to the baseline, we compare the identification accuracy under different compression ratios r, and it is obvious that when r = {2, 4, 8, 16, 32}, with the increase of the compression ratio r, the average identification accuracy slowly decreases, but it is still within the acceptable range. 2) Complexity of Different Compression Ratios: We also consider the complexity of the KG-AFC algorithm under different compression ratios. The model complexity is divided into time complexity and space complexity. The time complexity determines the training and testing time of the model. The smaller the highest order of time complexity, the better the time performance of the algorithm. If the time complexity is too high, it will lead to an increase in the running time and space of the model, which is undoubtedly unfavorable for the rapid verification and prediction of the model. Generally, we consider that all input data are of equal probability, that is to say, calculate the average time complexity. We can use floating-point operations (FLOPs) to measure the time complexity of the model. Because the classification of the KG-AFC architecture is mainly realized by the convolution layer and the AFC strategy is realized by the convolution layer, this article mainly considers the time complexity of the convolution layer. The time complexity formula can be expressed as
TSingle ∼ O(SM × SK × Cin × Cout) (23)
where SM represents the output size of the single convolution layer; SK represents the size of the convolution kernel; and Cin and Cout represent the number of input and output channels of this layer, respectively. Hence, the time complexity of the whole neural network [11] can be expressed as
TAll ∼ O
( N ∑
l=1
SMl × SKl × Cl−1 × Cl
)
(24)
where N represents the depth of CNN. In addition, the space complexity determines the number of parameters of the neural network, we define it as
SpaceAll ∼ O
( N ∑
l=1
×SKl × Cl−1 × Cl
)
. (25)
According to the above formula, the illustration of the time and space complexity for KG-AFC is shown in Fig. 7. From the model complexity of each compression ratio, we observe
