Fig. 4. Illustration of the schematic of the visualization interface of the RF signal feature library using MySQL Workbench.
Fig. 5. Illustration of visual representation diagram of RF signal KG.
that with the increase of compression ratio, both time complexity and space complexity decrease. The simulation results are also in line with our original purpose of introducing the AFC block, that is, to effectively reduce the amount of computation and reduce the complexity of the model through FC. Combined with the simulation results of identification accuracy and computational complexity under different compression ratios, it is not difficult to see that the performance is robust for a certain range of compression ratios, but the computational complexity decreases significantly with the increase of compression ratios, especially in the case of uncompressed and r = 2. To sum up, we choose the compression ratio of r = 8 to achieve the maximum balance between
performance and complexity. The compression ratio can effectively reduce the computational complexity without reducing the identification accuracy.
D. Advantages of Performance and Overhead
To verify the advantages of the proposed KG-AFC method in terms of performance and computation overhead, we carry out some comparative experiments.
1) Comparative Experiments: The selected SEI methods include three ML-based methods and two-DL based methods. kNN: This is one of the simplest and most commonly used classification algorithms in ML, which measures the distance
Authorized licensed use limited to: GUANGZHOU UNIVERSITY. Downloaded on September 25,2024 at 02:59:11 UTC from IEEE Xplore. Restrictions apply.


HUA et al.: SPECIFIC EMITTER IDENTIFICATION USING ADAPTIVE SIGNAL FEATURE EMBEDDED KNOWLEDGE GRAPH 4731
Fig. 6. Illustration of the box plots of identification accuracy for KG-AFC.
between different feature values for classification. Here, let the value of k as 3.
OneVsRestClassifier (Gupta et al. [27]): This is an ML-based method, which is an improved version of SVM and can be applied in multiclassification scenarios. This method equips each label with a classifier. For each classifier, the classification will be fitted with other classifications. DMEL (Wang et al. [28]): This is an ML-based method. This method embeds features through nine complex convolutional layers and three FCs while utilizing metric learning to classify features. RVCNN (Wang et al. [5]): This is a DL-based method. This method consists of nine convolutional layers and three FCs, of which three FCs are its classifiers.
MSCNN (Zhang et al. [33]): This is a DL-based method. This method extracts features from three receptive fields through different convolution kernels and carries out feature fusion to make them complete SEI tasks through the classifier. The classifier selected by MSCNN is three FCs.
2) Performance Comparison: We compared the identification accuracy of these methods above, and the simulation results are shown in Fig. 8. According to the simulation results of different SEI methods, we can conclude that the proposed KG-AFC has the best identification accuracy. In addition, this also indicates that the KG-AFC algorithm can effectively emphasize important features and ignore unimportant features during feature reconstruction to improve performance. 3) Overhead Comparison: We compared the computation overhead of these methods above, and the simulation results are shown in Table V. As is shown in Table V, the DL-based SEI methods often require longer training time than the ML-based SEI methods. While the ML-based DMEL, due to its direct processing of complex data, makes the calculation more complex, so the long training time is reasonable. Overall, the proposed KGAFC has significant advantages in training time, testing time, and total time compared to the cutting-edge DL-based SEI
Fig. 7. Illustration of the time and space complexity for KG-AFC.
Fig. 8. Illustration of the identification accuracy of different SEI methods.
methods, only inferior to the well-known kNN and improved SVM (OneVsRestClassifier) for their fast computation time. From the perspective of storage overhead, the proposed KGAFC outperforms all other SEI methods and even reduces storage overhead by 7–11 times compared to the same DLbased RVCNN and MSCNN. It can be seen that KG-AFC has considerable advantages in terms of storage overhead. It is worth noting that the storage overhead of the kNN is relatively high, as the kNN algorithm needs to save all training samples. Therefore, when the sample size is relatively large, the storage overhead will be high, so this result is reasonable. Combining identification accuracy and computation overhead, we can easily conclude that the proposed KG-AFC algorithm not only effectively improves identification accuracy but also exhibits advantages in computation overhead. It can achieve a good balance between performance and computation overhead. Meanwhile, the visualization assistance of KG enhances the model’s representation ability and further expands the application boundaries of KG.
