Guan Gui (Senior Member, IEEE) received the Ph.D. degree from the University of Electronic Science and Technology of China, Chengdu, China, in 2012. From 2009 to 2014, he joined Tohoku University, Sendai, Japan, as a Research Assistant and a Postdoctoral Research Fellow. From 2014 to 2015, he was an Assistant Professor with Akita Prefectural University, Akita, Japan. Since 2015, he has been a Professor with Nanjing University of Posts and Telecommunications, Nanjing, China. He has published more than 200 IEEE journal/conference papers. Prof. Gui won several best paper awards, e.g., ICC 2017, ICC 2014, and VTC 2014-Spring. He received the IEEE Communications Society Heinrich Hertz Award in 2021, the Elsevier Highly Cited Chinese Researchers in 2020–2022, the Clarivate Analytics Highly Cited Researcher in Cross-Field in 2021–2022, the Member and Global Activities Contributions Award in 2018, the Top Editor Award of IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON VEHICULAR TECHNOLOGY in 2019, and the Outstanding Journal Service Award of KSII Transactions on Internet and Information System in 2020. He is serving or served on the editorial boards of several journals, such as IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON VEHICULAR TECHNOLOGY. In addition, he served as the IEEE VTS Ad Hoc Committee Member in AI Wireless, the Executive Chair of ICCT 2023 and IEEE VTC 2021-Fall, the Symposium Chair of ICCC 2023, the Workshop Chair of LANTINCOM 2023, the TPC Chair of PRAI 2022, ICGIP 2022, PHM 2021, and WiMob 2020, the Vice Chair of WCNC 2021, the Symposium Chair of WCSP 2021, the General Co-Chair of Mobimedia 2020, the Track Chair of EuCNC 2021 and 2022, and IEEE VTC 2020 Spring, the Award Chair of PIMRC 2019, and a TPC Member of many IEEE international conferences, including GLOBECOM, ICC, WCNC, PIRMC, VTC, and SPAWC. He has been a Distinguished Lecturer of the IEEE Vehicular Technology Society since 2022 and he is also a Fellow of the Institution of Engineering and Technology.
Hsiao-Chun Wu (Fellow, IEEE) received the B.S.E.E. degree from National Cheng Kung University, Tainan, Taiwan, in 1990, and the M.S. and Ph.D. degrees in electrical and computer engineering from the University of Florida, Gainesville, FL, USA, in 1993 and 1999, respectively. From March 1999 to January 2001, he had worked with Motorola Personal Communications Sector Research Labs, Harvard, IL, USA, as a Senior Electrical Engineer. In January 2001, he joined the faculty with the Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, Louisiana State University, Baton Rouge, LA, USA, where he is currently a Distinguished Professor. From July to August 2007, he was a Visiting Assistant Professor with the Television and Networks Transmission Group, Communications Research Centre, Ottawa, ON, Canada. From August to December 2008, he was a Visiting Associate Professor with the Department of Electrical Engineering, Stanford University, Stanford, CA, USA. He is also a Visiting Professor with the International College of Semiconductor Technology, National Chiao Tung University, Hsinchu, Taiwan. He has published more than 320 peer-refereed technical journal and conference articles in electrical and computer engineering. His research interests include the areas of wireless communications and signal processing. Dr. Wu currently serves as a Senior Area Editor for IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON SIGNAL PROCESSING, an Associate Editor for IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON BROADCASTING, and an Editor for IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON COMMUNICATIONS and IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON MOBILE COMPUTING. Besides, he is an Academic Editor of Sensors. He served as an Editor and a Technical Editor for IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON WIRELESS COMMUNICATIONS and IEEE Communications Magazine and an Associate Editor for IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON VEHICULAR TECHNOLOGY, IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON SIGNAL PROCESSING, IEEE COMMUNICATIONS LETTERS, IEEE SIGNAL PROCESSING LETTERS, and IEEE Communications Magazine. He is an IEEE Distinguished Lecturer.
Hikmet Sari (Life Fellow, IEEE) received the Engineering Diploma and Ph.D. degrees from ENST, Paris, France, in 1978, and the Habilitation degree from the University of Paris XI, Bures-sur-Yvette, France, in 1980. From 1980 to 2002, he held various research and management positions with Philips Research Laboratories, Bengaluru, India; SAT, New York, NY, USA; Alcatel, Nanterre, France; Pacific Broadband Communications, San Jose, CA, USA; and Juniper Networks, Sunnyvale, CA, USA. From 2003 to 2016, he was a Professor and the Head of the Telecommunications Department, SUPELEC, Gif-sur-Yvette, France, and a Chief Scientist with Sequans Communications, Paris. He is currently a Professor with Nanjing University of Posts and Telecommunications, Nanjing, China. Dr. Sari’s distinctions include the Andre Blondel Medal in 1995, the Edwin H. Armstrong Achievement Award in 2003, the Harold Sobol Award in 2012, as well as election to the Academia Europaea (Academy of Europe) and the Science Academy of Turkey in 2012. He was the Chair of the Communication Theory Symposium of ICC 2002, the Technical Program Chair of ICC 2004 and EuCNC 2015, the Vice General Chair of ICC 2006, the General Chair of PIMRC 2010, WCNC 2012, and ICUWB 2014, an Executive Chair of WCNC 2014 and ICC 2017, the General Co-Chair of IEEE BlackSeaCom 2015, ATC 2016, ATC 2018, and PIMRC 2019, and an Executive Co-Chair of ICC 2016 and GLOBECOM 2023. He is currently serving as the General Chair of WCNC 2021. He served as an Editor for the IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON COMMUNICATIONS from 1987 to 1991, an Associate Editor for the IEEE COMMUNICATIONS LETTERS from 1999 to 2002, and a Guest Editor for several special issues of the IEEE JOURNAL ON SELECTED AREAS IN COMMUNICATIONS, European Transactions on Telecommunications, and other journals. He served as a Distinguished Lecturer of ComSoc from 2001 to 2006 and a member of the IEEE Fellow Evaluation Committee from 2002 to 2007 and the IEEE Awards Committee from 2005 to 2007.
